The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	New Delhi: Instead of indulging in trivialities and slapping show cause notice on players for a pub brawl, the BCCI should address the bigger issues plaguing Indian cricket, said former Pakistan captain Wasim Akram.    
	Trying to find out what happened in a pub in St Lucia is much lesser an issue than (having) unfit players or players hiding injuries. Under the circumstances, the BCCI slapping show-cause notices to a mix of senior and junior players is just beating around the bush, Akram said.        
	Calcutta: Talented wicket-keeper-batsman Shreevats Goswami has been selected for a three week training camp for the upcoming wicket-keepers at the newly opened BCCI Academy in Chennai from May 25 to June 16 under the guidance of Sameer Dighe and Vijay Dahiya.        
	London: Outgoing ICC Anti-Corruption and Security Unit (ACSU) chief Paul Condon Thursday gave clean chit to the third edition of IPL. IPL III seems to have been a very clean event said Condon.        
	Calcutta: England quick Graham Onions has been ruled out for up to twelve weeks as scans confirmed an ongoing bone stress reaction in his back. Onions also underwent surgery on Wednesday at a London hospital to repair cartilage in the front of his left knee.        
	New Delhi: Top seeds Mahesh Bhupathi and Max Mirnyi suffered a shock defeat but Rohan Bopanna and Aisam-ul-Haq Qureshi eased into the semi-finals of the ATP 250 event in Nice, France. Bhupathi and Mirnyi lost 3-6, 3-6 to the Italian pair of Andrea Seppi and Potito Starace. Bopanna and Qureshi, however, won 6-3, 6-2 against Colin Fleming and Ken Skupski.           
	New Delhi: An uphill task awaits India in this years womens hockey World Cup in Argentina where they have been clubbed alongside reigning World and Olympic champions the Netherlands and formidable teams like Germany and Australia. Japan and New Zealand are the other two teams in Pool A along with India.         
	Calcutta: Magma defeated Indian Chamber of Commerce 4-0 in the five-a-side invitational football tournament for The Telegraph Cup 2010 presented by McDowells No. 1 Celebration .    
	RESULTS: Magma 4 Indian Chamber of Commerce 0; Apeejay Surrendra 1 Vodafone 0; Shamsara Shipping 2 Medica Hospital 0; PWH Coopers 4 Siemens 0; IBM 4 The Telegraph 0; HSBC Bank 1 Wesman 1; Wipro 0 Jayshree Tea 2     
